When a small group of living creatures (small population) separates from the main population from which it originates (for example, if it moves across a range of mountains or a river or if it moves to a new island, where it is not possible to crosses or from a mountain range, or if it or if it or if it originates and from a mountain or river or a mountain or is not a river, it is to a mountain or is it originates or is not a river
This new environment has different resources and different rivals, so a new population will need different traits or adaptations to be a strong rival compared to what it needed before.
The original population has not changed at all, but they still need the same adjustments as before.
Over time, the new population begins to adapt to its new environment and begins to look less and less like the other population.
After thousands or even millions of years, the two populations will look so different that they can no longer be called the same species.
This process is called speciation, which means the formation of new species.
